    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-04-24T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-04-24T06:00:00-05:00" n="149"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d149">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00/1100: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Norway</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Oslo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-04-24T12:00:00+01:00"
                            >April 24, 1939—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received April 24—8:55
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>19. My 18, April 22, 1 p.m.<note n="38" xml:id="d149fn38">Not printed.</note>
                    Foreign Office informs me that the Foreign Minister replied orally in the
                    negative to the German Minister’s questions whether Norway felt itself
                    threatened by Germany and whether the Norwegian Government had “authorized” or
                    in other way had occasioned the President’s message but that the Foreign
                    Minister had added that obviously Norwegians, Norway knew, would be in danger if
                    there were a general war and that therefore Norway was putting its neutrality
                    guard in readiness.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
